  "texts": [
    "One way to resolve this kind of worry is to establish a principle of unity for an object.",
    "For example, we might rely on the idea of a functionally integrated system to capture the intuition that only someone's unshed hairs are properly part of her body (they still function to keep the body warm, wick away sweat, etc.).",
    "This functional principle is conceptually prior to the idea of a mereological sum that might conform to it since we must grasp the principle before we can say which of the indeterminately many candidates is the sum of parts of this functional unity.",
    "Anscombe wants to say something similar of action: actions are not -or not only -composites of atom-like events arranged in a causal network but have a unified structure that is prior to their redescription in terms of components or consequences.",
    "This analogy brings us around to the following question: what is the corresponding principle of unity of an action?"
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}